is a Windows component that enables high-performance bitmap composition with transforms, effects, and animations. Application developers can use the DirectComposition API to create visually engaging user interfaces that feature rich and fluid animated transitions from one visual to another.","pos":[1824,2133],"nodes":[{"content":"DirectComposition is a Windows component that enables high-performance bitmap composition with transforms, effects, and animations.","pos":[0,131]},{"content":"Application developers can use the DirectComposition API to create visually engaging user interfaces that feature rich and fluid animated transitions from one visual to another.","pos":[132,309]}]},{"content":"When to use","pos":[2149,2160]},{"content":"DirectComposition is designed to simplify the process of composing visuals and creating animated transitions. If your game requires complex user interfaces, you can use DirectComposition to simplify the creation and management of the UI.","pos":[2177,2414],"nodes":[{"content":"DirectComposition is designed to simplify the process of composing visuals and creating animated transitions.","pos":[0,109]},{"content":"If your game requires complex user interfaces, you can use DirectComposition to simplify the creation and management of the UI.","pos":[110,237]}]},{"content":"For more information","pos":[2430,2450]},{"content":"See the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DirectComposition<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh437371)</ept> documentation.","pos":[2467,2570],"source":"See the [DirectComposition](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh437371) documentation."}]},{"content":"Audio - APIs concerning playing audio and applying audio effects.","pos":[9149,9214]},{"content":"For information about using the audio APIs in your game, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Audio for games<ept id=\"p1\">](working-with-audio-in-your-directx-game.md)</ept>.","pos":[9215,9338],"source":" For information about using the audio APIs in your game, see [Audio for games](working-with-audio-in-your-directx-game.md)."},{"pos":[9344,11001],"content":"<table>\n<colgroup>\n<col width=\"50%\" />\n<col width=\"50%\" />\n</colgroup>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"header\">\n<th align=\"left\">API</th>\n<th align=\"left\">Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"odd\">\n<td align=\"left\">XAudio2</td>\n<td align=\"left\"><p>XAudio2 is a low-level audio API that provides a foundation for signal processing and mixing. XAudio is designed to be very responsive for game audio engines while maintaining the ability to create custom audio effects and complex chains of audio effects and filters.</p>\n<p><strong>When to use</strong></p>\n<p>Use XAudio2 when your game needs to play sounds with minimal overhead and delay.</p>\n<p><strong>For more information</strong></p>\n<p>See the [XAudio2](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh405049) documentation.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"even\">\n<td align=\"left\">Media Foundation</td>\n<td align=\"left\"><p>Microsoft Media Foundation is designed for the playback of media files and streams, both audio and video, but can also be used in games when higher level functionality than XAudio2 is required and some additional overhead is acceptable.</p>\n<p><strong>When to use</strong></p>\n<p>Media foundation is particularly useful for cinematic scenes or non-interactive components of your game. Media foundation is also useful for decoding audio files for playback using XAudio2.</p>\n<p><strong>For more information</strong></p>\n<p>See the [Microsoft Media Foundation overview](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ms694197).</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","leadings":["","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    "],"nodes":[{"content":"API","pos":[116,119]},{"content":"Description","pos":[142,153]},{"content":"XAudio2","pos":[216,223]},{"content":"XAudio2 is a low-level audio API that provides a foundation for signal processing and mixing. XAudio is designed to be very responsive for game audio engines while maintaining the ability to create custom audio effects and complex chains of audio effects and filters.","pos":[249,516],"nodes":[{"content":"XAudio2 is a low-level audio API that provides a foundation for signal processing and mixing.","pos":[0,93]},{"content":"XAudio is designed to be very responsive for game audio engines while maintaining the ability to create custom audio effects and complex chains of audio effects and filters.","pos":[94,267]}]},{"content":"When to use","pos":[532,543]},{"content":"Use XAudio2 when your game needs to play sounds with minimal overhead and delay.","pos":[560,640]},{"content":"For more information","pos":[656,676]},{"content":"See the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAudio2<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh405049)</ept> documentation.","pos":[693,786],"source":"See the [XAudio2](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh405049) documentation."},{"content":"Media Foundation","pos":[837,853]},{"content":"Microsoft Media Foundation is designed for the playback of media files and streams, both audio and video, but can also be used in games when higher level functionality than XAudio2 is required and some additional overhead is acceptable.","pos":[879,1115]},{"content":"When to use","pos":[1131,1142]},{"content":"Media foundation is particularly useful for cinematic scenes or non-interactive components of your game. Media foundation is also useful for decoding audio files for playback using XAudio2.","pos":[1159,1348],"nodes":[{"content":"Media foundation is particularly useful for cinematic scenes or non-interactive components of your game.","pos":[0,104]},{"content":"Media foundation is also useful for decoding audio files for playback using XAudio2.","pos":[105,189]}]},{"content":"For more information","pos":[1364,1384]},{"content":"See the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Microsoft Media Foundation overview<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ms694197)</ept>.","pos":[1401,1508],"source":"See the [Microsoft Media Foundation overview](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/ms694197)."}]},{"content":"Input - APIs concerning input from the keyboard, mouse, gamepad, and other user input sources.","pos":[11014,11108]},{"pos":[11114,13765],"content":"<table>\n<colgroup>\n<col width=\"50%\" />\n<col width=\"50%\" />\n</colgroup>\n<thead>\n<tr class=\"header\">\n<th align=\"left\">API</th>\n<th align=\"left\">Description</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr class=\"odd\">\n<td align=\"left\">XInput</td>\n<td align=\"left\"><p>The XInput Game Controller API enables applications to receive input from game controllers.</p>\n<p><strong>When to use</strong></p>\n<p>If your game needs to support gampad input and you have existing XInput code, you can continue to make use of XInput. XInput has been replaced by Windows.Gaming.Input for UWP, and if you're writing new input code, you should use Windows.Gaming.Input instead of XInput.</p>\n<p><strong>For more information</strong></p>\n<p>See the [XInput](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/desktop/hh405053) documentation.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"even\">\n<td align=\"left\">Windows.Gaming.Input</td>\n<td align=\"left\"><p>The Windows.Gaming.Input API replaces XInput and provides the same functionality with the following advantages over Xinput:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Lower resource usage</li>\n<li>Lower API call latency for retrieving input</li>\n<li>The ability to work with more than 4 gamepads at once</li>\n<li>The ability to access addition Xbox One gamepad features, such as the trigger vibration motors</li>\n<li>The ability to be notified when controllers connect/disconnect via event instead of polling</li>\n<li>The ability to attribute input to a specific user (Windows.System.User)</li>\n</ul>\n<p><strong>When to use</strong></p>\n<p>If your game needs to support gamepad input and is not using existing XInput code or you need one of the benefits listed above, you should make use of Windows.Gaming.Input.</p>\n<p><strong>For more information</strong></p>\n<p>See the [<strong>Windows.Gaming.Input</strong>](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn707817) documentation.</p></td>\n</tr>\n<tr class=\"odd\">\n<td align=\"left\">Windows.UI.Core.CoreWindow</td>\n<td align=\"left\"><p>The Windows.UI.Core.CoreWindow class provides events for tracking pointer presses and movement, and key down and key up events.</p>\n<p><strong>When to use</strong></p>\n<p>Use Windows.UI.Core.CoreWindows events when you need to track the mouse or key presses in your game.</p>\n<p><strong>For more information</strong></p>\n<p>See [Move-look controls for games](tutorial--adding-move-look-controls-to-your-directx-game.md) for more information about using the mouse or keyboard in your game.</p></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>","leadings":["","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    ","    "],"nodes":[{"content":"API","pos":[116,119]},{"content":"Description","pos":[142,153]},{"content":"XInput","pos":[216,222]},{"content":"The XInput Game Controller API enables applications to receive input from game controllers.","pos":[248,339]},{"content":"When to use","pos":[355,366]},{"content":"If your game needs to support gampad input and you have existing XInput code, you can continue to make use of XInput. XInput has been replaced by Windows.Gaming.Input for UWP, and if you're writing new input code, you should use Windows.Gaming.Input instead of XInput.","pos":[383,651],"nodes":[{"content"